   this new organization can outweigh the drawbacks. The drawbacks come
   from the fact that there is less of a pooling effect in the new
   organization than in the original one. The benefits come from the better
   human resource management that results in a higher efficiency of the
   agents, both in terms of speed and quality of the answers they provide
   to customers. Our analysis is supported by the use of some simple
   queueing models and provides some interesting insights. In particular,
   it appears that for some reasonable ranges of parameters, the new
   organization can outperform the original organization. We then extend
   the analysis to the case where, in addition to the identified customer
   portfolios, there is an additional flow of calls called out-portfolio
   flow. It is shown that this feature makes the new organization even more
   efficient.
